The former student representative council president faces charges of public violence theft malicious damage to property and assault with intent to cause grievous bodily harm following his arrest at his Wits residence in October.Dlamini s legs were chained while he was in the custody of Correctional Services officers and he walked into the dock and greeted people in the benches of the public gallery. The appellant is fixed with R2000 bail and the conditions are that he is ordered to desist from unlawfully disrupting the academic activities of Wits " said High Court Judge Ratha Mokgoatlheng in a sitting in the Palm Ridge Magistrates Court. He is entitled to participate in lawful activities on the campus not interfere with the charges against him and is prohibited from communicating with witnesses. On Tuesday Dlamini's legal representatives advocate Dali Mpofu and Tembeka Ngcukaitobi argued that Dlamini's arrest and prosecution was as a result of a political conspiracy.They based that argument on a meeting involving National Director of Public Prosecutions Shaun Abrahams that took place at the African National Congress headquarters Luthuli House on 10 October.Dlamini was denied bail after a three-day hearing in the Johannesburg Magistrates Court nine days after that meeting.Wits students and workers have turned up at the court at all his appearances to show their support for Dlamini. TMG Digital